		<p><blockquote><i>It is not education, wealth, or political might that keeps people from life; everything that a people once had, but has now lost, this is why they are unhealthy and morally fallen. Only health and morality guarantee the life of the people.</i></blockquote></p>

	<h4>Miroslav Tirsh</h4>
		<p>In East Central Europe sports developed different meanings than in Western Europe because of the imposition of imperial policies towards various, and often mutually exclusive, national ideas. The tension between different nations and ethnic groups, living in states whose borders were constantly shifting, overlapped with athletic practice. Sports became an opportunity for the legal and public representation of the nation, a means of declaration and articulation of wider social, cultural and political ideas, and opportunity to demonstrate the achievements of various groups. </p>	
		<p>In the second half of the 19th century the «Sokol» («Falcon» in Slavic languages) groups became popular in the Habsburg Empire. These were created on the model of the German gymnastics societies (turnverein). The Sokol organizations could be considered the key organization in the modern physical education of Slavic peoples. The first Sokol associations created workshops on the initiative of Miroslav Tirsh in 1862 in Prague. The Sokol movement quickly spread among other Slavic peoples—Slovenians, Croatians, Serbs, Macedonians, Poles, and Ukrainians. </p>
		<p>In Galicia the Poles first created a Sokol association in 1867, and from 1867-1884 there existed one association in Lwów. From 1884, however, there appeared a network of such associations across Galicia. The first mass meeting of Sokol groups – zlot – occurred in 1892 in Lwów. The number of members of the organization grew quickly. In 1893 there were 45 societies (with 5640 members) united in the Związek Polskich Gimnastycznych Towarystw Sokolich (Union of Polish Sokol Gymnastics Societies) in the Austro-Hungarian empire, but by 1914, 261 societies were active (with close to 30 000 members). </p>
		<p>Austrian Ukrainians founded their own Sokol (or Sokil in Ukrainian) organization in 1894 on the foundation the statute of the Czech Sokol. The primary initiators were Vasyl Nahirnyi and Volodymyr Lavrivskyi. But it was during the of Ivan Boberskyi from 1908-1914 that the organization acquired a mass character. In 1914 the society included 70 000 members belonging to 974 branches active all across Galicia. </p>
		<p>The primary activity of the Sokol societies was gymnastics—the performance of free exercises and exercises with equipment, with a stick, a spear, etc. National specificity appeared in the use of particular instruments. For example, Ukrainians performed exercises with a hatchet, flag, wreath, handkerchief and hand towel. Popular among all Sokol groups were the «towers»—gymnastics figures formed by athletes. In addition to practicing gymnastics and sports, popular activities included hiking and fire-fighting. Sokol groups created music and theater groups, organized concerts, evening parties and performances. The most popular practice was local and regional mass rallies (zlot in Polish, zdvyh in Ukrainian). </p>
		<p>Like other Sokol societies, the activity of Polish and Ukrainian groups was framed by national rhetoric, and gymnastics was united with cultural, educational and paramilitary practice. On the eve of war the Polish and Ukrainian gymnastics societies became a platform for the emergence of paramilitary organizations, such as the Ukrainian «Sichovii Striltsi» and the Polish organization «Shooting Association» (Związek Strzełecki).</p>
	<h4>“Muscular Judaism”</h4>
